<subSubSection id="C31B6527FFE0FFC22D88FA14C93A674E" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BBE36ACFFE0FFC22D88FA14C93A674E" blockId="32.[151,1436,994,1580]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B975EABEFFE0FFC22D88FA14CA0F64BE" bold="true" box="[198,343,1474,1500]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a Latin compound name that stems from the adjective 
<emphasis id="B975EABEFFE0FFC229B7FA15CE6764BE" box="[1273,1343,1475,1500]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">gilvus</emphasis>
(= pale yellow) and the adjective 
<emphasis id="B975EABEFFE0FFC22C8BFA3DC95C6766" box="[453,516,1515,1540]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">albus</emphasis>
(= white). I refer to the light coloration of the pronotum and the profusely distributed pale setae on the pronotal disc.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
